text:
What to report in the manuscript

Re-extraction (the &gt; 0.5 set). Returning to the source PDFs for the 12 effect sizes that disagreed most, the design-blind re-derivation reproduced the point estimates wherever the data are discrete counts (mean |Δd| vs Jones = 0.00; vs Davies = 0.83), corrected Jones on the single-group / vs-chance studies (a 4/n phantom-control variance inflation from the 50/50 rule, with halved N), and isolated Davies as the divergent extraction — via different outcome constructs, escalc artifacts, a sign error, and one defensible pool-vs-split. This is an independent re-derivation, not a validation against Jones: the point-estimate agreement is expected for discrete counts and the variance was no longer reverse-engineered to match.
Overlap. Of 37 Jones & DuVal studies, 29 are shared with Davies; 8 are unique to Jones (28 effect sizes).
Agreement. Across 52 comparable effect-size pairs, Jones-converted and Davies magnitudes correlate at Pearson r = 0.79 (65% within tolerance), rising to r = 0.89 among studies where both teams extracted the same number of effect sizes.
Direction of disagreement. Mean Bland–Altman bias = -0.14 d-units, indicating Davies reports slightly larger magnitudes on average; most large discrepancies trace to different outcomes extracted (behaviour-type columns) or different effect-size partitioning, not to the metric conversion.





